    description: "Glenn Dennis (March 24, 1925 – April 28, 2015) was a mortician and ambulance driver employed at Ballard Funeral Home in Roswell, New Mexico. His account of the Roswell incident is among the most widely known in popular culture — and simultaneously the most vigorously challenged by researchers on both sides of the debate. His testimony illustrates the complexity of evaluating witness accounts decades after events.\n\nTHE PHONE CALLS\n\nDennis asserted that on or around July 5, 1947, he received a series of phone calls from the mortuary officer at Roswell Army Air Field. The Ballard Funeral Home held the contract to provide ambulance and mortuary services to the base, making such calls within the normal course of business.\n\nHowever, the content of the calls was highly unusual. According to Dennis, the caller requested information about the availability of small, hermetically sealed caskets — child-sized — and inquired about preservation techniques for bodies that had been exposed to the elements for an extended period. The caller seemed particularly interested in whether embalming fluid would alter the chemical composition of tissue. Dennis found the questions strange but answered them professionally.\n\nDennis later stated that he made inquiries and determined that the base did not have any child fatalities on record, deepening the mystery of why child-sized coffins were needed.\n\nTHE BASE HOSPITAL ENCOUNTER\n\nDennis claimed that he later drove an injured airman to the base hospital in the Ballard Funeral Home ambulance. While at the hospital, he said he noticed unusual activity — military ambulances with debris in the back, heightened security, and a general atmosphere of urgency.\n\nAccording to Dennis, he encountered a nurse he knew who was visibly distressed. She warned him to leave immediately. Dennis stated that when he attempted to enter further into the facility, he was confronted by military police who threatened him with severe consequences if he ever spoke about what he had seen or heard at the base.\n\nDennis claimed the nurse later met with him privately and described assisting in the examination of small, non-human bodies — diminutive beings with oversized heads and small, delicate features. She reportedly made sketches for Dennis on a prescription pad or napkin.\n\nTHE NURSE — CREDIBILITY CRISIS\n\nThe nurse's identity became the central credibility problem in Dennis's account. When first publicly telling his story in 1989 (through an interview with researcher Stanton Friedman, more than four decades after the events), Dennis provided a name for the nurse. When researchers found no military records matching that name at Roswell AAF, Dennis changed the name — claiming the first had been a pseudonym to protect the real nurse's identity.\n\nExtensive searches of military records have failed to verify the existence of either named nurse at Roswell Army Air Field during the relevant period. The U.S. Air Force investigation in the 1990s found no documentation of a nurse matching Dennis's descriptions. Potential staff matches identified by researchers arrived at the base nearly a month after the claimed incident timeline.\n\nThis unresolved identification problem significantly undermines the most dramatic element of Dennis's account. Without a verified nurse, the body examination story rests entirely on Dennis's uncorroborated claim.\n\nCONTEMPORANEOUS CORROBORATION\n\nHowever, Dennis's account is not entirely without supporting evidence. Multiple individuals have independently confirmed that Dennis told them about unusual phone calls from the base requesting small coffins years or even decades before Roswell became a public sensation. This contemporaneous corroboration — people who heard his story long before there was any incentive to fabricate — is significant.\n\nDennis's story first became public in August 1989, more than four decades after the events. His 42-year silence before speaking publicly could be interpreted either as evidence that the military threats effectively suppressed his account, or as time during which a story could develop and grow in the telling.\n\nSTORY EVOLUTION\n\nCritics have documented that Dennis's account became more detailed and dramatic over time — a pattern that could indicate either recovered memories and increased comfort with disclosure, or progressive embellishment. Key details present in later tellings were absent from earlier versions. Supporters counter that this pattern is common with traumatic memories recalled after long periods of silence and that the core elements remained consistent.\n\nLATER LIFE AND LEGACY\n\nDennis co-founded the International UFO Museum and Research Center in Roswell in 1991, alongside Walter Haut. He remained a prominent figure in the Roswell community and a regular speaker at UFO-related events until his death.\n\nDennis's involvement with the museum and Roswell tourism industry has been cited by critics as a potential motivation for maintaining and embellishing his story. Supporters note that the museum was founded long after Dennis first shared his account privately and that his involvement speaks to genuine conviction rather than opportunism.\n\nGlenn Dennis died on April 28, 2015, at the age of 90.\n\nSources: Dennis's 1989 interview with Stanton Friedman, Randle & Schmitt \"The Truth About the UFO Crash at Roswell\" (1994), Carey & Schmitt \"Witness to Roswell\" (2007), USAF investigation findings (1994/1997), contemporaneous corroboration documented by multiple researchers."
