    description: "Grady L. \"Barney\" Barnett (1896–1969) was a civil engineer employed by the U.S. Soil Conservation Service in Socorro, New Mexico. He is reportedly among the first civilians to have encountered wreckage and bodies connected to the broader Roswell events of July 1947. His account — surviving entirely through second-hand testimony — represents both a tantalizing piece of the puzzle and a cautionary example of the challenges in evaluating decades-old witness accounts.\n\nTHE MALTAIS TESTIMONY\n\nBarnett's story became known through his friends Jean and Vern Maltais, who stated that Barnett told them the following account in the early 1950s, years before Roswell entered public consciousness.\n\nAccording to the Maltaises, Barnett said that while conducting field work on the Plains of San Agustin in early July 1947, he came upon a metallic disc-shaped craft. As relayed by his friends: \"Barney said he found a metallic disc the color of dirty stainless steel, twenty to thirty feet across, and there were four small bodies near the wreckage — beings in gray suits, four to five feet tall, with oversized heads.\" The beings were clearly not human, and Barnett was deeply shaken by what he had seen.\n\nBarnett reportedly told the Maltaises that a group of archaeologists from a nearby university also arrived at the site — they had apparently stumbled upon the wreckage independently while conducting a field project. Before either the civilian group or the archaeologists could investigate further, the military arrived, cordoned off the area, and warned everyone present that they must never speak about what they had seen. Barnett said he was told the incident was classified and that discussing it could result in serious consequences.\n\nTHE LOCATION PROBLEM\n\nThe Plains of San Agustin are located in west-central New Mexico, approximately 150 miles west of the Foster Ranch near Corona where the primary Roswell debris was found. This geographic separation created a significant problem for Roswell researchers.\n\nSome investigators, notably Stanton Friedman and Don Berliner in \"Crash at Corona\" (1992), argued that the San Agustin site represented a second, separate crash location — perhaps where the main body of a craft came down after shedding debris over the Foster Ranch. This \"two-site\" theory was an early attempt to reconcile Barnett's account with the known debris field.\n\nHowever, later research by Kevin Randle and Donald Schmitt concluded that the San Agustin connection lacked sufficient evidence to support it. They noted that the 150-mile separation made a connection to the Foster Ranch debris physically implausible without additional evidence, and that no independent witnesses had been found to corroborate a crash on the Plains of San Agustin. By the mid-1990s, most Roswell researchers had moved the focus away from the San Agustin location, though the question remains unresolved.\n\nTHE ARCHAEOLOGISTS\n\nBarnett's mention of archaeologists who independently discovered the wreckage is one of the most intriguing — and most frustrating — details in the Roswell case. Despite extensive research spanning decades, no university archaeological team has been confirmed as conducting fieldwork in the San Agustin area during early July 1947. Several candidates have been proposed and investigated, but none have been conclusively verified.\n\nThe absence of identified archaeologists does not necessarily disprove Barnett's account — university field records from 1947 are often incomplete, and academic teams working in remote New Mexico would not necessarily have left detailed daily records of their location. However, the inability to locate these corroborating witnesses significantly weakens the account.\n\nCREDIBILITY CONSIDERATIONS\n\nAll of Barnett's testimony is second-hand. He died in 1969, a full decade before Stanton Friedman's research revived public interest in Roswell. No researcher was ever able to interview Barnett directly. His account survives entirely through what he told friends and through entries in his wife Ruth's diary, which referenced his distress about something he had seen but did not provide the level of detail the Maltaises reported.\n\nHowever, Barnett was by all accounts a highly respected, steady individual. His career with the Soil Conservation Service required precision and reliability. Colleagues and neighbors described him as honest and not prone to fabrication or exaggeration. His standing in the community provides a baseline of credibility that researchers have noted, even while acknowledging the fundamental limitation of second-hand testimony.\n\nThe fact that Barnett told his story in the early 1950s — long before any financial or cultural incentive existed to claim involvement with the Roswell case — is significant. The Maltaises had no reason to fabricate their account of what their friend told them.\n\nToday, the Barnett account is largely treated separately from the core Roswell narrative centered on the Foster Ranch. Whether it represents a genuine second crash site, a conflated memory, or a misidentified event remains one of the open questions in Roswell research.\n\nSources: Jean and Vern Maltais testimony, documented in Moore & Berlitz \"The Roswell Incident\" (1980), Friedman & Berliner \"Crash at Corona\" (1992), Randle & Schmitt \"The Truth About the UFO Crash at Roswell\" (1994), Carey & Schmitt \"Witness to Roswell\" (2007), Ruth Barnett diary references."
